📌 Concept Explanation

Every VPC requires an IPv4 CIDR block, which defines the range of private IP addresses available within the network.

For example:

10.0.0.0/16

This means the VPC can allocate addresses from:

10.0.0.1
...
10.0.255.254

These addresses are private and are used by resources such as:

EC2 Instances
RDS Databases
Load Balancers
ECS Tasks
EKS Worker Nodes
Understanding CIDR Notation

CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) combines an IP address with a prefix length.

Example:

10.0.0.0/16

Where:

10.0.0.0 → Network address
/16 → First 16 bits identify the network

Common VPC CIDR sizes include:

CIDR	Approximate IP Addresses
/24	256
/20	4,096
/16	65,536

AWS reserves five IP addresses in every subnet, so the usable number is slightly lower.

Network Architecture
                     AWS Cloud
┌────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                    │
│      VPC (10.0.0.0/16)             │
│                                    │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────┐   │
│  │     Future Subnets          │   │
│  │                             │   │
│  │ 10.0.1.0/24                 │   │
│  │ 10.0.2.0/24                 │   │
│  │ 10.0.3.0/24                 │   │
│  └─────────────────────────────┘   │
│                                    │
└────────────────────────────────────┘

The VPC acts as the parent network, while subnets divide the address space into smaller segments for different workloads.

